h3. Summary

Unable to create oAuth application link with non Atlassian applications.


h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Deploy a clean JIRA 7.7.x or 7.8.x instance;
# Set the Base URL accordingly;
# Go to the application link page and create an application link for a non-Atlassian application;
# Once created, click on the Incoming/Outgoing authenticators options in order to configure the oAuth tokens;

h3. Expected Results
* To be able to configure the oAuth settings properly without the missing Base URL alert (_JIRA's base URL is set to undefinied but you are accessing JIRA from_)
* The external app to connect to JIRA properly;


h3. Actual Results
* The below alert related to the missing Base URL is thrown even if the Base URL is properly configured. If we click on the update the Base URL link and close the alert window, we're able to configure the oAuth settings, however, it does not work to connect from an external application.
 !Screen Shot 2018-03-05 at 11.59.44.png|thumbnail! 

h3.Solution / Workaround
* Use JIRA 7.6.3 where the issue does not occur and the external application is able to connect to JIRA properly.

h3. +Scenario+

In JIRA Cloud, it's possible to create and transition an issue using this endpoint:
{code:java}
/rest/api/2/issue{code}
Sample JSON body:
{code:java}
{ 
	"fields": {
		"project": {
			"key": "TEST"
		},
		"summary": "Test Summary",
		"description": "Test Description",
		"issuetype": {
			"name": "Story"
		}
	},
	"transition": {
		"id": "21"
	}
}
{code}
(+) According to [Cloud REST API doc|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/rest/#api-api-2-issue-post], it seems the *transition* parameter has been enabled and works as intended.

(-) This however doesn't work in JIRA Server. With the same endpoint and JSON body, an issue is created but *not transitioned*. According to [Server REST API doc|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/7.8.0/#api/2/issue-createIssue], it seems *transition* hasn't been enabled.
h3. +Suggestion+
# Enable *transition* for JIRA Server REST API so that an issue can be created and transitioned with this single endpoint:
{code:java}
/rest/api/2/issue{code}
# *Document this feature clearly* in the respective docs above.
(/) It's even better to have a full checklist of differences between Cloud and Server REST APIs.

h3. +Workaround+

For JIRA Server, once an issue is created, take note of its ID in the response, e.g.:
{code:java}
{
    "id": "12407",
    "key": "TEST-31",
    "self": "http://10.60.2.88:8770/jira770/rest/api/2/issue/12407"
}
{code}
then use this (POST) endpoint to transition it:
{code:java}
/rest/api/2/issue/12407/transitions{code}
Sample JSON body:
{code:java}
{ 
	"transition": {
		"id": "21"
	}
}
{code}

h4. Suggestion Description
[Jira Server REST API|https://developer.atlassian.com/server/jira/platform/rest-apis/] is a simple resource that help administrators to perform operations that would take some time of their day to day activities in a couple seconds, instead of a couple minutes.

Turns out that there are several ways to make the API more secure, like for instance, interacting with SAML/OKTA or even using a Token Based authentication in-app. The intent of this suggestion is to enable the use of resources like SAML/OKTA for the REST API or to enable a Token Based authentication to provide secure communication in between client and application.

h4. Feature Requests for different applications
The same request already exists for Confluence ([CONFSERVER-54412|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-54412]), will be released for BitBucket ([BSERV-2722|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/BSERV-2722]) and has been requested to Bamboo ([BAM-12095|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/BAM-12095]) as well.

h4. Sample Payload
Currently, if we want to create an issue, we would need to execute below call:
{code:java}
curl -D- -u "adminuser:adminpassword" -X POST --data {see below} -H "Content-Type: application/json" http://localhost:8080/rest/api/2/issue/
{code}
{code:java}
{
    "fields": {
       "project":
       { 
          "key": "TEST"
       },
       "summary": "REST ye merry gentlemen.",
       "description": "Creating of an issue using project keys and issue type names using the REST API",
       "issuetype": {
          "name": "Bug"
       }
   }
}
{code}
As can be seen above, we do need to send an username and password at the header of the request to have it working properly, which is considered insecure. This is what we would like to avoid.

h3. Summary
Invalid error when trying to create component using rest with only projectId

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Create a component using 
{code}
{
"name": "Component 1",
"projectId": 10000
}
{code}

h3. Expected Results
The component should be created or a valid error about the project name must be specific should be returned. 

h3. Actual Results
A project id must be specified for this operation.
{code}
{
"errorMessages": [
"A project id must be specified for this operation."
],
"errors": {}
}
{code}
 
h3. Notes/Workaround
Only using the project name works
{code}


{
    "name": "Component 2",
    "project": "TEST"
}

{code}

Hi,

Steps:
# Fire REST Request: {{https://server.de/rest/api/2/issue/ABC-1234}}
{code}
JSON: {"fields":{"customfield_123456":"something"}}

{code}
# Error returned "400: "Field 'customfield_123456' cannot be set. It is not on the appropriate screen, or unknown."

Initially thought of a different reason for this error, apparently user does not have an 'Edit Issue' permission so with the same request, just granting permission works.

Jira Version: 7.7.1

Suggested error message: '401: "The calling user does not have permission to edit the issue.'

Issue similar to: https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-44003
Derived from Support Ticket: https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/browse/DEVHELP-976
